article.description:
Barbara Turner, Maria Conlon and Ann Strother
combined for 43 points as Connecticut (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today; No. 3 Associated Press) beat South Florida
72-56 Saturday.
article.headline: Taurasi sits out after hurting ankle in practice
article.linkText: No. 2 UConn wins handily without top scorer Taurasi
article.story:
TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Far from home, the Connecticut women's basketball team still had plenty of people on its side.

In fact, most of the 3,702 fans at the Sun Dome -- the most ever to see the South Florida women on their home court -- cheered for Connecticut (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today; No. 3 Associated Press) in its 72-56 victory Saturday night.

Even with junior All-American Diana Taurasi on the bench with a swollen right ankle, the defending national champion Huskies (10-0) easily extended the second-longest winning streak in history to 49 games.

"They're a lot better than their record,'' Connecticut coach Geno Auriemma said. "There are some teams that are 4-5 that are really lousy. South Florida is not one of them.''

Connecticut hasn't lost since falling 90-75 to Notre Dame in the 2001 NCAA Final Four. Louisiana Tech set the all-time mark with 54 in a row from 1980-82.

Barbara Turner led the Huskies with 16 points. Maria Conlon added 14 and Ann Strother added 13.

Sarah Lochmann scored 12 points and Jameelah Trimble had 11 to
lead South Florida (4-6), which has lost four consecutive games.

The Bulls limited Connecticut to 39 percent shooting from the floor. The Huskies compensated for the absence of Taurasi, their leading scorer with a 19.4 average, by holding South Florida to 35 percent.

Taurasi sat out after injuring her ankle in practice Friday.

"I was afraid that all of a sudden guys would just go crazy, trying to make up for (Taurasi),'' Auriemma said. "Everybody did a little bit, and that's what a good team is supposed to be like.''

Taurasi, who also averages seven points and six rebounds, has had recurring ankle problems since high school. Her status is questionable for Monday's game at Florida State.

"I don't think I've ever seen the kid make a face or grimace. She is one of the toughest people I've ever been around,'' Auriemma said. "She could have played tonight, and you probably wouldn't have known that she's hurt.''

South Florida coach Jose Fernandez said the matchup against a national power brought more good than harm to his program.

"It helps you out in all facets. I haven't seen more excitement in the Tampa Bay area in our university since I've been here,'' the third-year coach said.

"I'm a firm believer that even though we lost tonight, this game helped us out in unbelievable magnitude,'' Fernandez said.
